@edition "2026.6"

-- D1(xvi) frontier guardrail. This program is VALID (it type-checks clean — a `_test`,
-- not a `_bad`), but it uses a `for` COMPREHENSION (`for (x in xs) -> x * 2`). eval builds
-- a list by evaluating the body for each element (with optional filter clauses); the
-- compute spine has no comprehension lowering — `normComp`/`tail` reach the `For` AST node
-- and refuse it. The differential harness must report it `unsupported` — a CLEAN refusal at
-- the compiler frontier, never a miscompile.
--
-- This is the backend-slice analogue of a `_bad` twin: a backend slice adds no checker
-- rejection rule, so the guarantee under test is "the compiler refuses what it cannot
-- yet lower, loudly", asserted by the harness rather than by an error count. D1(ii)
-- moved the frontier PAST scalar `match`; D1(iii) PAST tuples; D1(iv) PAST ADT
-- constructors; D1(v) PAST records; D1(vi) PAST lists; D1(vii) PAST closures-as-values;
-- D1(viii) PAST first-class `def` references; D1(ix) PAST first-class BUILTIN references;
-- D1(x) PAST short-circuit `&&`/`||`; D1(xi) PAST non-tail `if` as a value; D1(xii) PAST
-- non-tail `match` as a value; D1(xiii) PAST multi-clause `def`s; D1(xiv) PAST reassignment;
-- D1(xv) PAST atom literals; D1(xvi) PAST duration literals (folded `5s` → `5000`; see
-- compile_duration_test). The frontier now sits at `for` COMPREHENSIONS. This file uses one,
-- so it still refuses; when comprehensions lower (a later D1 slice, a map/filter spine), it
-- flips from `unsupported` to a print with no edit.

def doubled(xs: List(Number)): List(Number)
  for (x in xs) -> x * 2

def main(): Effect [io] ()
  println(doubled([1, 2, 3]))
